These two lines run **immediately** when the script is executed:

    var one = document.getElementById(&quot;industryid&quot;);
    
    var two = document.getElementById(&quot;industryid&quot;).value;

That means that if the element doesn&#39;t exist (yet), you&#39;ll get `null` for `one` and the second line will fail. But if the element exists (for instance, if the `script` is after the `select` in the HTML), you&#39;ll get the element in `one` and `&quot;&quot;` in `two`, because nothing is selected in the select.

You want to get the value **later**, when processing the click. And since `getElementById` is really, really fast, there&#39;s no reason not to do that then, too:

    function reply_click()
    {
        console.log(document.getElementById(&quot;industryid&quot;).value);
    }

